                    <h2 class="text-center">A* Research
                        
                    </h2>
                    <p>Artificial intelligence, particularly in the context of video games, has always been an interest of mine.  I've often felt that for all of the excitement built up over upgrades in the graphics of games, not enough uproar is created at the lack of improvement in the AI in the majority of modern games.  One particular field of AI that I find particularly interesting is that of pathfinding.</p>
                    <p>A* (pronounced A Star) is a pathfinding algorithm that is used in a variety of contexts beyond video games.  However, most of my research has been exclusive to the video game side of the algorithm.  Characters, or units, in most games use a pathfinding algorithm to move from point A to point B in a level.  If only one unit were to move at a time, there would be no problems with A* and units should be able to flawlessly make the shortest moves possible to reach their destinations.  A problem arises when multiple units move simultaneously.  If two units are ordered to move directly toward each other to a destination on the other side of the opposing unit, they will inevitably walk straight into each other and then look unintelligent while they attempt to navigate around each other.  I spent time researching a modified version of A* called Hierarchical Cooperative A* which aims to eliminate this problem by taking other units movement over time into consideration when plotting movement routes.</p>
                    <p>To assist myself in visualizing the problem with A*, I created an applet in Java full of "nodes" where a unit can occupy space.  Within the applet, users can create custom pathfinding scenarios, or choose from any of 3 troublesome types of pathfinding situations.  These randomly generated, yet predefined, scenarios include a bottleneck, a random grid full of units and walls, and a setup where every unit on the map must reach their destination directly across the map from their starting points.  Also included in the applet is the ability to run massive amounts of tests with no visual element for data analysis.</p>
                    <p>Source code for tool available <%= link_to "on Github.", "https://github.com/LayfieldK/astar_research" %></p>
                    <p>Or download the tool and <%= link_to "use it yourself.", "https://s3.amazonaws.com/kevinlayfieldsite/AStarTool.jar" %>  Note that you must have a JRE installed on your machine to run the jar file, and also that this tool was made for myself, so it is not extremely user friendly.</p>
