                    <h2 class="text-center">The Lanista
                        
                    </h2>
                    <p>Back before I started devouring everything I could related to ancient Rome, I watched the show Spartacus.  I loved the first season of that show, and often found myself more interested in Batiartus' story over Spartacus'.  Batiartus played the lanista, or the owner of the gladiator school, and was constantly faced with decisions regarding his gladiators, upcoming tournaments, backroom dealings, and politics.  I felt that this role would fit perfectly into a game.  Instead of being the heroic gladiator, the player could be the calculating lanista.</p>
                    <p>The Lanista is a turn based strategy game where players must build up their ludus (gladiator school), and gain fame quickly enough to be invited to the opening games of the Colosseum.  Along the way, the player will face choices over how to teach their gladiators, how to handle disobedient gladiators, how to best eliminate rival lanistas, and how to earn the notice of top politicians.  Inevitably, most of the action of the game will take place in the arena, where the player will be given the option to command his gladiators in battle.  Whether they listen to you or not is another story.  Do they respect you?  Do they fear you?  Or do their own motives drive them more than your influence?</p>
